# GitHub Actions Standards

## Security
- Pin all third-party actions to full commit SHA, not tags
- Set minimum `permissions` on every workflow; never use default (write-all)
- Use OIDC (`id-token: write`) for AWS/cloud auth; avoid stored long-lived credentials
- Never interpolate untrusted input in `run:` blocks (e.g., `${{ github.event.issue.body }}`)
- **Trigger safety:** avoid `pull_request_target` with `actions/checkout` on PR head; treat `workflow_run` and `issue_comment` triggers as privilege-escalation vectors — they inherit repo write access and can be triggered by external contributors on public repos
- Use environment-scoped secrets for production credentials
- **Runner security:** prefer GitHub-hosted runners for public repos; self-hosted runners must restrict network access (no broad egress), run ephemeral (no persisted state between jobs), and never be shared across trust boundaries (public + private repos on same runner = secret leakage risk)

## Workflow Structure
- One workflow per concern (CI, deploy, release)
- Use `concurrency` groups to prevent duplicate runs
- Set `timeout-minutes` on all jobs (default 360 min is too long)
- Use `cancel-in-progress: true` on PR workflows
- Add `if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'` guards on deploy jobs

## Reusable Workflows
- Extract shared logic into reusable workflows (`workflow_call`)
- Pass secrets explicitly or use `secrets: inherit`
- Keep nesting under 4 levels
- Use composite actions for reusable step sequences

## CI Best Practices
- Run lint, test, and build as parallel jobs
- Cache dependencies with `actions/cache` or built-in setup caching
- Use matrix strategy for multi-version testing
- Upload artifacts for build outputs; download in deploy jobs
- Use `needs:` to express job dependencies

## Deployments
- Use GitHub Environments with protection rules for staging/production
- Require reviewers for production deployments
- Deploy via reusable workflow with environment as input
- Use `environment.url` to link deployment status to live URL

## Artifact Integrity and Supply Chain
- Sign container images and critical build artifacts (e.g., cosign, Sigstore)
- Generate provenance metadata for builds (SLSA provenance via `actions/attest-build-provenance` or equivalent)
- Produce SBOM for container images; store alongside the artifact in registry
- Verify signatures and provenance in deployment workflows before promoting artifacts to production

## Maintenance
- Add Dependabot config for `github-actions` package ecosystem
- Review and audit third-party actions quarterly
- Use `gh run list` and `gh run view` for workflow debugging
